{
  "answer": "In *The Wanderer*, **wyrd** is introduced as an inexorable, impersonal force: \"Wyrd is wholly steadfast!\"[^1] It governs all worldly change, as in \"the decree of the Fates changes the world under the heavens,\" and explicitly defies resistance: \"A weary mind cannot withstand Wyrd.\"[^2]\n\nIn *Manusmṛti*, **daiva** names a lawful marriage rite: \"The gift of a daughter, after having adorned her, to a priest who is duly officiating at a sacrifice while it is in progress, they call the `Daiva` rite.\"[^3] It carries no explicit metaphysical discussion of fate here (or elsewhere in the work); the term denotes ritual submission during a divine sacrifice rather than cosmic inevitability.\n\nThe corpus lacks metaphysical treatment of *daiva* as \"fate\" (distinct from its ritual use across *Manusmṛti*, *Nāradasmṛti*, and *Viṣṇu Smṛti*), so no direct comparison of \"fate\" metaphysics is possible. Under *wyrd*, one may stoically endure exile and seek heavenly grace; no parallel \"action\" appears for *daiva* qua fate.\n\n[^1]: *Old English Elegies*, \"The Wanderer\" [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-9cca5e).\n\n[^2]: *Old English Elegies*, \"The Wanderer\" [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-9462cc).\n\n[^3]: *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 3 [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/03/translation/#p-7c3179).",
